The paper presents algorithms for solving NP-hard problems such as Subset Sum and Knapsack, which are typically studied in the area of computational complexity (cs.CC) and data structures (cs.DS). The use of random access to random bits suggests that information theory (cs.IT) may also be relevant. The paper also mentions the problem of determining whether two lists share a common value, which could fall under computational geometry (cs.CG) or discrete mathematics (cs.DM).
